# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigan was the son of a surgeon and was born at Waiblingen in 1677.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/adam-gottlieb-weigen] He studied theology at Württemberg but also took interest in anatomy and natural science.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen became a pastor and advocate of pietism in Leonberg.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigan was influenced by the writings of Philipp Spener.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen argued for a compassionate treatment of the animals from a Christian theological framework.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/adam-gottlieb-weigen] In 1711, Weigen authored *De Jure Hominis in Creaturas*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/adam-gottlieb-weigen] It has been described as "the first work ever to deal with the topic of animal rights as a general theme." The book became known in Denmark and inspired Laurids Smith.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/adam-gottlieb-weigen] Weigen moved to Wahlheim, where he died in 1727.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] In the 1990s and 2000s, Alasdair Cochrane studied politics at the University of Sheffield and the London School of Economics (LSE).
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] His doctoral thesis, supervised by Cécile Fabre with Paul Kelly acting as an adviser, was entitled *Moral obligations to non-humans*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He subsequently became a fellow and lecturer at the LSE.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] During this time, Cochrane published articles in *Res Publica*, *Utilitas* and *Political Studies* presenting aspects of his interest-based theory of animal rights, which is defended in the final chapter of *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] The book was Cochrane's first, and the political theorist Robert Garner acted as an important discussant during the writing process.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane establishes the book as a work of normative political theory asking to what extent animals should be included in the domain of justice.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] States can and do regulate human-animal relationships, whether the animals in question are used in agriculture, as companions, or in some other way.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane's focus is not on why laws are passed or on comparing laws, but in exploring what kind of laws *should* be passed.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] As his focus is on political theory, he is less concerned with questions about individual moral obligations than he is with institutional arrangements.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He notes, however, that questions about animals have been neglected in political theory.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] In the second chapter, Cochrane considers the history of thinking on the relationship between justice and animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He argues that within ancient philosophy there was disagreement about the inclusion of animals within accounts of justice, in medieval Christian philosophy there was a consensus that they should be excluded, and in modern philosophy there has been a return to disagreement.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Chapter three considers utilitarianism, according to which the rightness or wrongness of an action is determined by the extent to which it promotes *utility*—a concept equated, by classical utilitarians, with pleasure.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] As a political theory, then, classical utilitarianism entails that "it is the obligation of political communities to formulate policies and institutions which promote pleasure".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Utilitarianism as a whole, Cochrane argues, posed a challenge to the medieval and early modern assumption that animals are owed nothing.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Its focus on welfare and sentience, and its egalitarian nature, allow the extension of justice to animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane then defends Singer's account both against those presenting arguments in defence of speciesism, and against critics (such as R.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Frey) who maintain that animals do not have interests.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He then considers utilitarian critics of Singer, who argue that meat-eating maximises utility, even when animal interests are taken into account.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] This leads to the criticism that judging the best consequences is an extremely difficult task for political communities, but Cochrane concludes that a utilitarian consensus does at least support the abolition of factory farming.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Finally, he addresses critics who argue that Singer's position offers insufficient protection for animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Martha Nussbaum's argument that animals can suffer unfelt harms is considered, as is Tom Regan's criticism that, under Singer's account, animals are protected only insofar as their protection maximises welfare, rather than in their own right.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Chapter four considers liberalism, a political theory which, according to Cochrane, has as its defining feature a valuation of "the free and equal individual person".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane focuses primarily upon John Rawls, whose social contract account offers two reasons for the rejection of animals from issues of basic justice: questions of reciprocity, for which animals are ill-suited, and questions of personhood, as all parties to the contract must be moral persons.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane criticises Rawls's exclusion of animals, before identifying the risks to animals inherent within liberal pluralism.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Modified versions of personhood that include animals are discussed.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane closes the chapter by arguing that personhood *and* welfare should both be considered important; in so doing, he points towards his own conception of justice for animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Chapter five assesses the relationship between animals and communitarianism.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Communitarians criticise liberalism's focus on a state which does not interfere with individuals, instead favouring a political order which takes a stand on moral concerns, drawing from the shared moral values of a given society.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane initially argues that communitarianism, using British society as an example, can be used to expand justice to animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He devotes the remainder of the chapter to four arguments against this line of thought.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] First, communitarianism is particularist; that is, the principles it expounds are wholly contingent on the values in the particular society.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Second, there are difficulties inherent in finding "authentic" values within a given society.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Third, societies often favour some animals over others, leaving unfavoured animals vulnerable.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Fourth, there is the question of whose values within a society matter: states often contain multiple communities with very different attitudes to animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Consideration of this fourth question involves analysis of multiculturalism.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane goes on, in chapter six, to consider Marxism.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Unlike the other political theories explored in *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory*, Marxism is purportedly not a normative account but a scientific theory which predicts and explains the end of the state and the beginning of communism.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] This is understood as the inevitable conclusion of the history of the changing forms of economic relationships.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane outlines the discontinuities between humans and animals that exist for Karl Marx and considers the extent to which animal-rights thinking is an example of bourgeois morality.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] These analyses serve to illustrate how Marxist thinking can be used to exclude animals, but counterarguments are offered.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He next considers the work of David Sztybel and Ted Benton, who have drawn upon the adage of "From each according to his ability, to each according to his need" in relation to animals; Cochrane is wary about the use of the phrase for three reasons.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Finally, Cochrane considers Benton's proposal that liberal rights-based approaches to animal justice cannot achieve their goal, and that Marxism can be used as a resource for political achievement.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] This is, for Cochrane, Marxism's most important contribution in the area.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane considers feminism, the final tradition he examines, in chapter seven.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] As with Marxism, there are historical links between feminism and animal liberation.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane considers the putative interrelatedness, posited by some feminist theorists, of the oppression of animals and women, but denies that the liberation of animals and women are necessarily interdependent.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He suggests that there are four ways that this relationship could be grounded.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] The first is an idea taken from theorists drawing upon ecofeminism, like Josephine Donovan.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] This is the claim that the domination of women and animals are both due to a patriarchal elevation of the "rational" over the "natural".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Adams's argument that the connection of meat-eating and masculinity serves to oppress both women and animals, meaning that the liberation of both depends upon the end of meat-eating.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] The third is that, as identified by Adams and Catharine MacKinnon, women and animals are linked and oppressed by linguistic norms.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] For example, women might be called *cow*, *bitch* or *dog*, which serves to denigrate both women and animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] The fourth is the way that both animals and women are objectified, treated as mere things to be used towards the ends of others.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane argues that women are not irrational, though animals are less rational than humans, meaning that the oppression and liberation of the two groups may differ.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He challenges Adams's claims about meat by envisioning a vegetarian but misogynistic society on the one hand and a society where the genders are equal but meat continues to be eaten on the other.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He challenges the claims about language by observing that some animal-based insults are gender-neutral (for example, *rat*, *pig*, *sheep*), and some slurs to women (for example, *witch*, *jezebel*, *whore*) are unrelated to animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Concerning objectification, Cochrane notes that women are not considered property under the law, though animals are.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] This makes their respective objectification importantly different.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Next, the author rebuts five criticisms of reason-based approaches—epitomised, for Cochrane, by Singer and Regan—to animal liberation from thinkers supportive of feminist care-based approaches, before outlining and rejecting an emotionally driven, care-based approach to animal justice.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] In the final chapter Cochrane argues that each school has an important contribution to make to animal justice, particularly liberalism and utilitarianism.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He writes that, while talk of our political and moral obligations to animals is today more prominent than ever, it remains on the periphery of mainstream dialogue in political theory.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He closes by arguing that this neglect is a problem for political theory, and that animals are owed justice.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] If the book's claims are correct, Cochrane concludes, questions concerning the treatment of animals should be considered some of the most pressing political issues today.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane argues that while each of the schools of thought he has considered has problems, they all have something important to contribute to the debate.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Utilitarianism's most important contribution is its focus on sentience, but its major failing is its lack of respect for individuals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Liberalism, on the other hand, asserts the centrality of the individual.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Communitarianism, though it is too ready to attribute cohesion to the values of a given society, observes that individuals can flourish only within appropriate communities, and stresses the importance of changing the views of society at large.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] This latter idea is shared by Marxism, which points out that legal change does not necessarily equate to effective change.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] While Cochrane does not agree that capitalism must be overthrown, he recognises that "fundamental shifts in the organisation, norms and institutions of society" are needed for justice to be extended to animals.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Care-based feminist approaches, despite Cochrane's criticism, remind us that emotions and sympathy should not be ignored.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cochrane's own sympathies lie most strongly with utilitarianism and liberalism; his own account is most influenced by them.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He argues that rights derived from considerations of interests can protect individual animals and place limits on what can be done to them.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] These rights cannot be violated, even in the name of the greater good, which means that the cultural and economic practices of human beings will be affected.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Anticipating criticism, Cochrane explains that not every interest leads to a right.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] A full consideration of this argument is outside the scope of the book.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] The argument was expanded in Cochrane's *Animal Rights Without Liberation* (2012) which, though published after *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory*, was based on his doctoral thesis.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Palgrave Macmillan advertised the book with quotes taken from Cooke and Garner's respective reviews, as well as with quotes from Daniel A.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Dombrowski was quoted as saying that the "book will be welcomed by all who are interested in the relationship between non-human animals and political theory, a relationship that has been underexplored by scholars.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Cooke considered Cochrane's own account to be "interesting and worthy of further consideration" and found his supporting arguments to be "convincing", but he worried that the account was not considered in the depth it warranted.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He wrote that *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory* would have benefited if more space had been given to the interest-based account.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Further, Cooke noted that, in covering such a wide array of positions, Cochrane had to sacrifice depth of argument; Cooke considered this unproblematic, as readers could easily follow up the thinkers cited.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Seymour was particularly critical of Cochrane's coverage of feminism, which was, for him, "an unfortunate lapse in an otherwise fascinating review".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Seymour argued that Cochrane's critique was superficial or "[missed] the point entirely".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Instead, he suggested, feminist approaches provide a potentially highly productive approach to the subject.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Similarly, though Rasmussen praised the book's first five chapters as "providing an invaluable resource for undergraduates or scholars new to political theory", he felt that Cochrane's coverage of Marxism and feminism was somewhat less thorough.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] In response to *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory*, Garner raised two themes, the first of which was the use of the concept of *justice*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Agreeing with Cochrane that the concept is the defining feature of a political account, as opposed to more general accounts of animal ethics, Garner nevertheless found Cochrane's account of justice to be "too broad and loose".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] In the book, Cochrane considers justice for animals to be "about recognising that the treatment of animals is something that political communities ought to enforce for the sake of animals themselves".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Further, Garner suggests that Cochrane is "perhaps unduly uncritical of the utility of employing justice as a means to protect the interests of animals".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] He outlines two ways that animals might be protected without being the recipients of justice; first, they may be owed direct duties outside of justice, or, second, they might be protected by means of indirect duties, meaning that they are protected because of what humans owe to one another.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Despite raising these themes in his review of *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory*, Garner later rejected both possibilities in his own work, arguing that animals should be considered recipients of justice.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Rasmussen felt that Cochrane utilised a narrow account of the political, meaning that a range of feminist, post-colonial and post-humanist perspectives were ignored in the book.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] The second theme Garner identified was the divide between ideal and nonideal theory, which he understands as a way political theory may be used to contextualise animal ethics and further the debate.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Ultimately, for Garner, Cochrane's theory serves as a challenge to abolitionism, which, Garner fears, both polarises the debate and is unrealistic.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] The themes of this review were built upon in Garner's 2013 book *A Theory of Justice for Animals*.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] In the course of his review of the book, Garner looked forward to the release of Cochrane's second book, *Animal Rights Without Liberation*, which offers a lengthier defence of the interest-based rights theory.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Since the book's publication, a number of works exploring animals in political theory have been published; these works have been collectively referred to as belonging to the "political turn" in animal ethics/animal rights, or the disciplines of "animal political philosophy" and "Animal Politics".
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] Both *An Introduction to Animals and Political Theory* and *Animal Rights Without Liberation* have become an established part of this literature.
[src:an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory/an-introduction-to-animals-and-political-theory] The book has been published in paperback, hardback and eBook formats.
